esent volume. Significantly, some authors sought to emphasize the continuing history of prejudice and persecution, which reached a peak during the Nazi era and persisted after the war. Current questions of social integration in Europe, as well as that of ethnic definition and the construction of ethnic-national identity constitute another principal pillar of the book. The complexity of issues involved, such as collective memory, myth-making and social constructionism, trigger intense debate among researchers dealing with Romani studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHistory (General). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh  aEthnic relations, Holocaust, Human rights, Integration, Minorities, Nazism, Roma studies, Romanies.1 aAchim, Viorel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Yehuda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatz, Katalin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargalit, Gilad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatras, Yaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShahar, Shulamith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSobotka, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStauber, Roni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStauber, Roni, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTamás, Pál, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThurner, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVago, Raphael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVago, Raphael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWidmann, Peter, econtributor.